Other current fastEmbedR changes use high-level design ideas only, including
separating requested output k from a wider internal NN-descent graph degree and
evaluating overlapping batched all-neighbors graph construction.

KeOps design reference
----------------------

The exact t-SNE repulsion path in `src/tsne_neighbors.cpp` is informed by the
LazyTensor/map-reduce design used by KeOps:

  KeOps
  Repository: https://github.com/getkeops/keops
  Documentation: https://www.kernel-operations.io/keops/index.html
  License: MIT

fastEmbedR does not vendor, link to, or call KeOps, RKeOps, PyKeOps, PyTorch,
or Python at runtime. The implemented t-SNE change is package-native C++ and
currently internal/experimental: the all-pairs Student-t repulsive force can be
evaluated as a blocked online row-wise reduction with linear gradient memory,
while the sparse KNN attractive probabilities, early exaggeration,
momentum/gains, and zero-mean updates remain in the
fastEmbedR/Rtsne-neighbors-compatible optimizer. The faster pair-symmetric CPU
loop remains the default unless this path is explicitly selected for testing.

TorchDR design reference
------------------------

The InfoTSNE optimizer and experimental Metal UMAP optimizer selector
`FASTEMBEDR_METAL_UMAP_OPTIMIZER=torchdr` were informed by TorchDR's
negative-sampling neighbor-embedding structure:

  TorchDR
  Repository: https://github.com/TorchDR/TorchDR
  License: BSD-3-Clause

The fastEmbedR implementations are native C++ and Objective-C++/Metal code.
They do not vendor TorchDR source files, link to TorchDR, or call
Python/PyTorch at runtime.

For `infotsne()`, fastEmbedR translates the InfoTSNE objective structure:
sparse entropic KNN affinities for attraction and uniformly sampled negatives
for the repulsive `logsumexp(log Q)` term. The implementation in
`src/tsne_neighbors.cpp` uses closed-form native C++ gradients rather than
PyTorch autograd.

For the experimental Metal UMAP path, the translated idea is row-wise negative
sampling proportional to the number of active attractive neighbours in a Metal
kernel.

openTSNE design reference
-------------------------

The native t-SNE-from-KNN optimizer and the fixed-reference transform used by
`transform_tsne()` and `landmark_tsne()` were informed by openTSNE:

  openTSNE
  Repository: https://github.com/pavlin-policar/openTSNE
  License: BSD-3-Clause

For `embed_knn(method = "tsne")`, fastEmbedR now exposes an openTSNE-style
`negative_gradient_method` selector for native C++ `"bh"` and `"exact"` paths.
The implementation in `src/tsne_neighbors.cpp` follows openTSNE's separation
of sparse positive KNN forces from approximate negative forces. The current
native Barnes-Hut implementation is fastEmbedR C++ code; it does not call
Python/Cython.

For `transform_tsne()`, fastEmbedR follows the design of
`TSNEEmbedding.transform()` and `prepare_partial()`: initialize query points
from nearby reference embedding coordinates, compute asymmetric
query-to-reference affinities, optimize only the query coordinates against the
fixed reference embedding, and clip large transform gradients/steps.

The openTSNE FFT/FIt-SNE interpolation kernels are not yet ported. Explicit
requests for `negative_gradient_method = "fft"` fail clearly rather than
falling back to Python.

t-SNE-CUDA paper design reference
---------------------------------

The native Metal implementation of the fixed-reference transform also uses the
n-body/device-resident optimization framing described in:

  Chan DM, Rao R, Huang F, Canny J. t-SNE-CUDA: GPU-Accelerated t-SNE and its
  Applications to Modern Data. arXiv:1807.11824v1, 2018.

The corresponding implementation repository was also inspected:

  CannyLab/tsne-cuda
  Repository: https://github.com/CannyLab/tsne-cuda
  Commit inspected: 44249b6
  License: BSD-3-Clause

The transferred idea is architectural: keep reference coordinates, query
coordinates, gains, updates, and the repulsive-force loop on the GPU during
optimization, returning only the final layout. fastEmbedR does not vendor,
copy, link to, or call t-SNE-CUDA source code. The current Metal
implementation is a kernel for the openTSNE-style fixed-reference transform,
not a full Barnes-Hut/FFT t-SNE-CUDA port.

The package also exposes a native fastEmbedR exact CUDA t-SNE-from-KNN kernel
through `embed_knn(method = "tsne", backend = "cuda")` when CUDA support is
compiled in. This is a dense exact parity path; the CannyLab-inspired scalable
FFT/FIt-SNE repulsive-field port is retained as future CUDA/Metal work.
